---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import Hub from '~/layouts/Hub.astro';
import DirectoryCard from '~/components/DirectoryCard.astro';

const title = 'rabbit breeders in Singapore';
const description = 'why we do not list commercial rabbit breeders in Singapore, what the law allows, and where SG owners actually find their rabbits.';
const intro = 'short version: Singapore does not have ethical commercial rabbit breeders worth listing. we explain why, and where to go instead.';

const all = await getCollection('directory', ({ data }) => data.type === 'breeders' && !data.draft);
---
<Hub title={title} description={description} intro={intro}>
  <section class="prose mt-2 max-w-none">
    <h2>our position</h2>
    <p>
      we do not list commercial rabbit breeders in Singapore. this is a
      deliberate editorial choice, not an oversight. here is the reasoning, so
      you can decide whether you agree.
    </p>

    <h2>what the law allows in SG</h2>
    <p>
      under the <a href="https://www.nparks.gov.sg/avs" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Animal &amp; Veterinary Service (AVS)</a>,
      pet shops can legally sell rabbits with a valid licence. there is no
      separate licensing category for hobbyist or backyard rabbit breeding. the
      rabbits sold in SG pet shops are typically imported from overseas
      farms or bred locally in unlicensed backyard setups. neither pathway
      has the welfare oversight that responsible breeding requires —
      health screening of parents, lineage records, socialisation protocols,
      lifetime return policies.
    </p>

    <h2>what the SG rabbit community says</h2>
    <p>
      every active SG rabbit rescue — <a href="/rescues/the-stray-wabbit/">The Stray Wabbit</a>,
      <a href="/rescues/house-rabbit-society-singapore-hrss/">House Rabbit Society Singapore</a>,
      <a href="/rescues/bunny-wonderland-sg/">Bunny Wonderland</a>, and
      <a href="/rescues/spca-singapore/">SPCA Singapore</a> — handles
      pet-shop and breeder surrender cases regularly. the typical pattern is
      a rabbit bought on impulse, surrendered within 6-18 months once the
      owner discovers the work involved. promoting more buying makes that
      cycle worse.
    </p>

    <h2>where SG owners actually find their rabbit</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>adopt from a rescue.</strong> SG rescues have rabbits of every
        breed, age, and personality. they spay/neuter before adoption, give a
        rough age and known health history, and offer ongoing support.
        see the <a href="/rescues/">rescue directory</a>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>foster first.</strong> if you are unsure rabbits suit your life,
        most SG rescues run foster programmes. you take care of a rabbit for
        weeks, decide if you want to adopt, and the rescue covers vet costs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>community rehoming.</strong> SG rabbit Facebook groups and
        Telegram channels constantly have owners rehoming for migration or
        family changes. these rabbits are usually already neutered, litter
        trained, and come with their setup.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>if you still want to buy a rabbit from a pet shop</h2>
    <p>
      that is your decision and we will not gatekeep. before you do, please
      read <a href="/care/adopt-vs-buy/">adopt vs buy — SG rescues vs breeders honestly compared</a>
      and <a href="/care/cost-of-owning-rabbit-singapore/">the actual cost of
      owning a rabbit in Singapore</a>. ask the pet shop:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>what farm or breeder did this rabbit come from?</li>
      <li>has the rabbit been health-checked by a vet, and which one?</li>
      <li>what is your return policy if the rabbit develops a health issue in the first 30 days?</li>
      <li>what is the rabbit's date of birth, not just the import date?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      if any of those answers is vague, the shop has not done its homework.
      walk away.
    </p>

    {all.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2>directly listed (with caveats)</h2>
        <p>
          if a SG breeder or seller meets every welfare criterion above, we list
          them here with full caveats. all listings include lineage records,
          health-screening evidence, and a lifetime return policy.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-3 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          {all.map((e) => <DirectoryCard entry={e} />)}
        </div>
      </>
    )}

    <h2>related reading</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/care/adopt-vs-buy/">adopt vs buy — SG rescues vs breeders honestly compared</a></li>
      <li><a href="/care/cost-of-owning-rabbit-singapore/">cost of owning a rabbit in Singapore</a></li>
      <li><a href="/care/first-week-with-new-rabbit-singapore/">first week with a new rabbit in SG</a></li>
      <li><a href="/rescues/">rescue directory</a></li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-8 text-sm text-ink-soft">
      know a SG rabbit breeder who meets every welfare criterion above and
      is willing to share lineage, health records, and a written return
      policy publicly? <a href="/contact/">tell us</a> and we will verify.
    </p>
  </section>
</Hub>
